  "text": "The CRD validation schema to OpenAPI publishing chain in Kubernetes follows this path:\n\n## 1. CRD Validation Specification (JSONSchemaProps)\nCustomResourceDefinitions define validation schemas using JSONSchemaProps types. The main definitions are in:\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/apis/apiextensions/types_jsonschema.go` - Core JSONSchemaProps structure\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/apis/apiextensions/v1/types_jsonschema.go` - v1 API version\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/apis/apiextensions/validation/validation.go` - Validation logic\n\nJSONSchemaProps is a JSON-Schema Draft 4 compatible structure that can include properties like Type, Format, Pattern, Maximum, Minimum, Required, Items, Properties, etc.\n\n## 2. Structural Schema Extraction\nThe JSONSchemaProps from CRD validation specs are extracted and converted to an internal structural schema representation:\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/apiserver/schema/structural.go` - Defines the Structural type which represents a normalized schema\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/apiserver/schema/convert.go` - Contains NewStructural() function that converts JSONSchemaProps to Structural format\n\nThe Structural type separates concerns: Generic (Type, Description, Default, Nullable), Extensions (x-kubernetes-* fields), and ValueValidation (format constraints, composition operators like allOf/oneOf/anyOf).\n\n## 3. OpenAPI Schema Conversion\nStructural schemas are converted to OpenAPI v2 and v3 formats:\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/apiserver/schema/kubeopenapi.go` - ToKubeOpenAPI() method converts Structural to kube-openapi spec.Schema\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/controller/openapi/builder/builder.go` - BuildOpenAPIV2() and BuildOpenAPIV3() functions that orchestrate the full conversion, handling CRD introspection and REST API route generation\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/controller/openapi/v2/conversion.go` - ToStructuralOpenAPIV2() function that downconverts v3 schemas to v2-compatible format by removing unsupported fields like allOf/oneOf/anyOf\n\n## 4. OpenAPI Spec Publishing to API Server Endpoints\nThe converted OpenAPI specs are published through controllers that watch CRDs and register handlers:\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/controller/openapi/controller.go` - Watches CustomResourceDefinitions and publishes OpenAPI v2 specs using kube-openapi handler.OpenAPIService\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/controller/openapiv3/controller.go` - Watches CustomResourceDefinitions and publishes OpenAPI v3 specs using kube-openapi handler3.OpenAPIService\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/routes/openapi.go` - Registers the actual HTTP endpoints (/openapi/v2 and /openapi/v3) in the API server mux through InstallV2() and InstallV3() methods\n\n## 5. Supporting Infrastructure\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/apiserver/customresource_handler.go` - Uses structural schemas for custom resource validation and handling\n- `vendor/k8s.io/kube-openapi/pkg/builder/openapi.go` and `vendor/k8s.io/kube-openapi/pkg/builder3/openapi.go` - Build complete OpenAPI specs from web service routes\n- `vendor/k8s.io/kube-openapi/pkg/handler/openapi.go` and `vendor/k8s.io/kube-openapi/pkg/handler3/openapi.go` - Serve the constructed OpenAPI specs via HTTP endpoints\n\nThe entire pipeline ensures that CRD validation schemas are properly exposed as OpenAPI documentation that clients can use for API discovery and validation."
}

